				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Westerner&#8217;s Inside View of Alibaba Successes and Failures</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Barboza			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-16T17:04:04+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 16, 2014 1:04 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 16, 2014 1:04 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/a-westerners-inside-view-of-alibaba-successes-and-failures/" data-title="A Westerner&#8217;s Inside View of Alibaba Successes and Failures" data-description="In a Q. and A., Porter Erisman, a former Alibaba vice president who made a documentary about the company, discusses life at Alibaba&#039;s early days and working with Jack Ma.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/16/business/dbpix-alibaba/dbpix-alibaba-blog480.png" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/16/business/dbpix-alibaba/dbpix-alibaba-blog480.png" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/16/business/dbpix-alibaba/dbpix-alibaba-blog480.png" id="100000003003899" width="480" height="320" alt="âCrocodile in the Yangtze,â released in 2012, offers a largely positive portrayal of Alibaba."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">âCrocodile in the Yangtze,â released in 2012, offers a largely positive portrayal of Alibaba.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/05/06/business/dealbook/07alibaba-documents.html"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/document_icon.gif" alt="Documents" width="10" height="12" border="0"> Documents: Reports on Alibaba&#8217;s I.P.O.</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/05/06/business/dealbook/from-netscape-to-alibaba.html"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/graphic_icon.gif" alt="Graphic" width="11" height="11" border="0"> Graphic: From Netscape to Alibaba</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After studying Chinese in the early 1990s and hosting a travel show on state-run television in China, Porter Erisman went to work for a public relations firm. Then, during the dot-com boom in 2000, he joined a tiny, Chinese Internet start-up called Alibaba. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Erisman, who grew up in Colorado, was one of just a handful of Westerners working inside Alibaba shortly after it was founded in 1999.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He worked at the company as a vice president for international marketing and corporate affairs for eight years, watching it develop an online presence, demolish the Chinese operation of the American company eBay and grow into an e-commerce giant that was recently valued at $130 billion. Alibaba is now preparing to list its shares on the New York Stock Exchange in what could be the biggest stock offering in history.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When he left in 2008, he started work on a documentary about his experience at the company, hoping it might inspire other entrepreneurs and explain some of the challenges they could face in seeking to build their own company.</p>
<div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="FHlT3QxMqCs" data-start="">
<div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/FHlT3QxMqCs/0.jpg" />
<div class="playButton">
<div class="arrow"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="caption">A trailer for &#8220;Crocodile in the Yangtze,&#8221; a documentary on Alibaba.</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The result is âCrocodile in the Yangtze,â an hourlong documentary based on hundreds of hours of video footage Mr. Erisman collected, mostly from the archives of the company and other television outlets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The film, which was released in 2012, offers a largely positive portrayal of Alibaba as a scrappy and dynamic start-up, and Jack Ma as its flamboyant and relentless leader. But it also shows some of the companyâs internal struggles, and hints that it came close to collapse in 2001, when spending got out of control. The documentary, which is available on the video sharing website Vimeo on Demand, was awarded the best film on innovation and entrepreneurship at the Silicon Valley Film Festival.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Erisman, 44, answered questions about the company from David Barboza, the Shanghai bureau chief of The New York Times. This interview has been edited and condensed:</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> We now know that Alibaba is one of the worldâs biggest Internet companies. But what was it like when you joined the company in April 2000?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> When I joined Alibaba, the offices were shiny and new, with the energy and enthusiasm of a start-up that had &#8220;just graduated&#8221; from an apartment to a real office building. But when I walked around the office, I was surprised to find a room filled with 12 bunk beds and staff sleeping in the bunks. Even in the afternoon, it was a stuffy, dark room filled with the stench of 12 snoring engineers who had been working round-the-clock on the website. So while the company had &#8220;graduated&#8221; from an apartment (where staff often slept on the floor) to an office, some of the old habits had carried over. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was a good indication of how hard we&#8217;d be working over the next few years. When Savio Kwan joined the company as its chief operating officer, one of his first steps was to get rid of the room filled with bunk beds, arguing that it was unsustainable to have a mature company that had people sleeping in the offices round the clock. I was happy to see the bunk beds eventually go, but I admired their hard-working spirit.</p>
<div class="w592"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000002865514" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

    <figcaption class="caption">
        <h4 class="headline">What Is Alibaba?</h4>
		        <div class="caption-video">
                <div class="summary-credit">
            <p class="summary">The e-commerce company has seized investor and public interest to an extent that is unusual for a company that does much of its business in China.</p>
            <span class="credit video-credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder">
